My fellow ADHDers and/or depression, what do your symptoms look like when they‚Äôre out of control? What do you struggle with the most?

I feel so dysfunctional lately. I‚Äôm hanging on until January, where hopefully I can be medicated into either proper function or just straight up into numbness if nothing else works.
I look like I always do.

I lose everything. Constantly. It‚Äôs like having memory loss, absolutely no recollection of placing things down or picking them up. My mind is racing, it‚Äôs loud, with thoughts overlapping one another, and I want to scream. I can‚Äôt settle down, like to the point where it becomes painful to be up and moving but I genuinely cannot relax or pause. It‚Äôs like having 15 energizer bunnies attached to me with no direction. It‚Äôs genuinely awful and overstimulating

I have been struggling the most with the mood swings lately. One day I'm alright, but the next day I hit a wall and get down again and that lasts a few days.
When it‚Äôs bad all I can do is move from my bed to the couch and rot all day in my pajamas and then eventually go back to bed.
Same
Not being able to get any forward momentum, forgetting to do even the simplist things then getting super fucking pissed at myself for it
I was about to comment but read the other comments and yea, it's too embarrassing. I barely function.

Memory and the ability to get out of the panic paralysis. I have no working memory so I have to write down anything important and the ability to move from one task to another is still something I struggle with. Also the shame spiral. I spiral very easily and I takes DAYS for me to get out of the funk. The meds help with a the executive but it makes the anxiety so much worse.
Complete disassociation. Soreness. Hyperthinking. Anxiety. Worse case scenario. Full on Panic Attack with crying and heavy breathing and the need to hug myself in fear of dying.
Knowing everything you need to do and then watching yourself not do any of those things.

I often withdraw. I‚Äôve been able to mask through work on some of those days almost mechanically. The flux of emptiness and internal chaos is exhausting both mentally and physically. Sending you love and light my friend.

My ADHD symptoms and depression symptoms have some overlap but they‚Äôre definitely not the same. But when I‚Äôm struggling, my sleep is impacted first. I already have chronic insomnia but when depressed it gets so much worse. And then because I‚Äôm not sleeping regularly, I get agitated and lose my patience with people and want to withdraw into myself. Everything gets harder to do. I lose all my energy and the things that I normally enjoy start to feel meaningless.
Im grateful every day for science and for the pills that help me not think about un-aliving myself.

I hate my job, it takes up the vast majority of my time 5/7 days of the week.  On weekends, instead of feeling free I‚Äôm often paralyzed and stressed out because there is so much I want or need to do that I just need a nothing day to recover.  Then I have one day to actually accomplish my errands and have a little fun or visit with fam, then back fucking to it.
I yell (either in my head or out loud) ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt put down, put AWAY‚Äù and it sometimes works

When my depression is really bad I‚Äôm super irritable and have no patience. I struggle to even explain things or have discussions because I don‚Äôt have the energy and it annoys me. I eat very little and sleep a lot because getting up means I should do something productive and I don‚Äôt want to. üò©
That‚Äôs me on a mild one. Lol

For me it‚Äôs sitting there, mostly at work, with the intention to do something simple and then a half hour goes by and I‚Äôve done everything but what I intended to do. Then I get super frustrated because I‚Äôm aware of it but literally can‚Äôt make myself do it.

For me out of control adhd means a 20 minute frantic search for keys that are on my pocket.  Or the phone that is in my hand. It's disassociating at a key moment of every and any conversation.  It's making "careless" mistakes at work. Depression when is out of control is being bedridden for weeks or months. For me I can't medicate for adhd because I'm also bipolar II and stimulants cause mania.

I find my executive functioning and ability to think + focus clearly really takes a turn for the worse when my ADHD + depression flare. Making food takes way longer than usual, and self maintenance (teeth brushing) is more difficult. Fatigue worsens

I think that the chronic stress of *gestures at the state of everything* definitely isn't helping me. When I'm dysregulated, it tends to make everything else more difficult + my tendencies of spiraling into despair worsen. Crisis mode intensifies.

Executive function & ‚Äúthe wall of awful‚Äù. 

Struggling to prioritize & complete basic/essential tasks on the good days, struggling to even know where/how to begin on the bad ones. 

Also, regulating my emotions.

Magnesium glycinate, vit D (10,000IU) folate, vitamins b & 12 for mood regulation.

A *quality* sun lamp - daily. I use a Carex (brand).

Familiarizing yourself w ‚Äúthe wall of awful‚Äù.

My therapist dropped a truth bomb on me:
"high functioning depression is scary as hell because you're very capable of hiding emotions, feelings and thoughts, so no one knows you're not okay and even if you say something no one realises the severity, because you don't seem like someone who is mentally spiralling out of control."

I worked a high stress high level job in medicine for years. Cared deeply about every person I dealt with, was a great wife according to my husband and took care of an aging mother and mother in law among many tiger things. I did it all without blinking and put a damn smile on my face while I was absolutely breaking inside. I‚Äôd mention I wasn‚Äôt feeling ‚Äúlike my happy self‚Äù but nobody worried. One day I did break and it was bad. We‚Äôre talking full on mental breakdown. Nobody understood why.

Caring for my mid-stage dementia mom ‚Äî partially, since she lives in assisted living and I come visit from out of town every couple of weeks ‚Äî and running a business as well as trying to date and get healthy and enjoy my amazing city. "What'd you do this weekend?" "Oh, chilled out." = hid in my apartment and tried to do more than doomscroll and watch YouTube.
Facts‚Ä¶sometimes we don‚Äôt even know

I have a secundairy depression cause of chronic pain. You could also call that high functioning, reading what that entails. I recognized a lot in this post. People don‚Äôt even take you seriously if you do tell them you in need. After 11 years I‚Äôm sometimes ready to give up. That was called ‚Äòbullshit‚Äô by my stepdad. That hurts a damn lot. I‚Äôm getting punished for holding on so long, so my pain and depression aren‚Äôt real. I have endometriosis and no cure.

That‚Äôs the painful truth about high-functioning depression. When you're the one who "has it all together," people assume you're fine, even when you're drowning inside. You can show up, perform, and meet expectations, all while carrying an invisible weight that no one sees.

This is why self-awareness and support systems are crucial. Just because someone seems okay doesn‚Äôt mean they are. You deserve rest, support, and healing just as much as anyone else.

This is what clinical depression looks like.
It‚Äôs not always crying in the corner or staying in bed all day. Sometimes, it‚Äôs avoiding friends you used to love hanging out with. It‚Äôs losing interest in the hobbies that once made you feel alive. It‚Äôs eating more than usual ‚Äì not because you‚Äôre hungry, but because it‚Äôs the only thing that feels comforting for a while.

I‚Äôve gained weight, I can‚Äôt focus at work, and my back hurts almost every day. It‚Äôs not just tiredness ‚Äì it‚Äôs the weight of everything I keep carrying silently. Please remember: people who seem ‚Äúokay‚Äù might still be fighting a quiet battle. Be kind, always. üíô
